AUDIO: 'I\'ve been testing out Bernini R from ByteDance as they\'ve open-sourced both the inference code and model weights for their Bernini renderer. ComfyUI natively supports its image and video editing capabilities, so let\'s get to it. Hello'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and welcome to more nerdy rodent geekery. I have tons of Bernini workflow information for you today, and just in case you\'re not familiar with the channel, I like to use the rodent method'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for my workflows. This means clean layouts with named groups for stuff because I think that makes everything both easier to understand and to update. If you are using this tutorial to update'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your own workflows, don\'t forget you can pause to take screenshots or rewatch bits at any time. Also, if you find these videos helpful, prefer tutorials from actual humans, or perhaps you just'

[00:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like all this workflow stuff done for you already, then you can support the channel via the Patreon link in the video description. It\'s your support which lets me make even more workflows'

[01:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for you and to share these free video tutorials with everyone. That freedom to choose is, of course, yours and a huge thank you to all supporters because you make this possible. Starting with the'

[01:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'loader group then and being based on 1, it uses two separate transformer models for high noise and low noise denoising, which we can see here. Inference outputs are at 480p 16 FPS by default, but you'

[01:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can go up to 720p and use a higher FPS, which you\'ll see later on in this video. To make things even better, I\'ve packed the loader chock-full with nodes to not'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'only help improve image quality, but also to save precious VRAM. Let\'s take a look at these now. Like the node label indicates, this first one, 1 normalized attention guidance, is from KJ Nodes.'

[01:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Normalized attention guidance acts as a mathematical stabilizer that helps to prevent text prompts from distorting the video, keeping the generated output clean, stable, and highly detailed. If'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you want to use a negative prompt even at CFG 1, then at the flip of a switch, you can enable NAG. Skip layer guidance is a ComfyUI native node that provides a'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'training-free sampling technique which aims to dramatically fix broken shapes, morphing faces, and unstable movements in diffusion transformer architectures such as 1.2.'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Model sampling SD3 alters the noise schedule to help lock down video physics, whilst rescale CFG acts as a safety limiter to prevent high prompt'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'guidance from frying your colors. As we\'re using CFG 1, this essentially gives you a fine control, which can be useful for some schedulers and samplers. And finally, you may like to use KJ\'s'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sage attention patch and one chunk feedforward nodes to help save some of that VRAM. Don\'t forget to install Sage attention first if you do want to use'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that Sage attention node, of course. Like it says in my note, the amount of VRAM needed for this depends on a lot of factors including things such as video resolution, which task you\'re'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'performing, but for super low VRAM cards, do check out the original GitHub repo which features a tiny 1.3 B model. Anyway, I think that covers it for'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'options you can use in a ComfyUI model chain to start with. So, let\'s move on. After picking your model options, you\'ll want to use some sort of prompt a bit like the one I have here. Change to a cartoon style with a thin black outline'

[03:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and open her mouth. Your prompt acts as instructions to the AI, which in this case is for both an image style change and also a change to the subject\'s'

[04:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mouth. So, it\'s an image editing task. We\'ll see the actual image I\'m changing in just a second, but also notice you can use a negative prompt as well. It\'s in Chinese, but basically a negative'

[04:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt tells the model about things that you want to steer away from, such as blurry details and people walking backwards. It won\'t do a whole lot at CFG one though, unless you\'re using that'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'NAG node we looked at in the loader. As this model can do a variety of things, you may also like to have a look at their prompt enhancer linked there in the prompting note. Whilst this looks'

